@misc{DeBra,
abstract = {The structures of AHA! we have seen and the way in which they are created using the Concept Editor show a high resemblance with the AHAM reference model: You can create arbitrarily many concepts, each with an arbitrary set of attributes. The attributes cannot represent complex data types though, so AHA! is simpler than what the reference model allows. AHA! uses event-condition-action rules to perform user model updates. The order in which rules are executed is clear and sequential, which means there are no confluence problems. The rules may trigger each other and may trigger each other indefinitely. The concept editor can detect cycles but not every detected cycle indicates an infinite loop that is actually possible. The analysis is thus conservative. The connection between concepts and resources can be used for page selectors. In AHA! links can refer to resources or to concepts. In either case the AHA! engine will find a match between concept and resource. Through the casegroup feature it is possible to select conditionally included objects. This is part of the process of page construction. Creating an application through the Concept Editor is a lot of work because for every concept the attributes need to be created manually and every adaptation rule has to be created as a “specific adaptation rule”. This makes application creation very error-prone as well as laborious. The Graph Author Tool was created to solve these problems and to allow authoring to be done at a higher level of abstraction. The Graph Author knows about concept types, concept relationship types and offers “generic adaptation rules” that are associated with concept relationship types. The event-condition-action rules used by the AHA! engine are all generated automatically through a compiler that performs “rule instantiation”.},
